---
import { Globe, Compass } from "@lucide/astro";
import { slide } from "astro:transitions";
import BackRow from "../components/BackRow.astro";
import { siteConfig } from "../data/site";
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

export const prerender = true;

const structuredData = [
  {
    "@type": "AboutPage",
    "@id": `${siteConfig.url}/about/#about`,
    url: `${siteConfig.url}/about/`,
    name: "About a9x",
    description:
      "A personal look at how a9x sees the world, what catches their attention, and how they spend their time.",
    mainEntity: {
      "@id": `${siteConfig.url}#person`,
    },
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title="about | a9x"
  description="A personal look at how a9x sees the world, what catches their attention, and how they spend their time."
  pageType="AboutPage"
  ogType="profile"
  structuredData={structuredData}
>
  <article
    class="page page--interior"
    transition:name="page"
    transition:animate={slide({ duration: "0.28s" })}
    tabindex="-1"
    data-page
  >
    <div class="page-header">
      <h1 class="page-title" transition:name="about-title">about</h1>
      <p class="page-subtitle">a little about how i see things</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Hero Quote -->
    <div class="about-hero-quote" aria-label="Opening quote">
      <div class="about-hero-quote__mark" aria-hidden="true">&ldquo;</div>
      <blockquote class="about-hero-quote__text">
        Even after all this time, the sun never says to the earth &lsquo;you owe
        me.&rsquo; Look what happens with a love like that — it lights the whole
        sky.
      </blockquote>
      <cite class="about-hero-quote__attribution">— Hafiz</cite>
    </div>

    <!-- Section 1: How I See the World -->
    <section class="about-section" aria-label="How I see the world">
      <div class="about-section__header">
        <span class="about-section__icon" aria-hidden="true"><Globe /></span>
        <h2 class="about-section__title">how i see the world</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="about-divider" aria-hidden="true">
        <span class="about-divider__line"></span>
      </div>

      <div class="about-section__body">
        <p>
          i grew up in new jersey. i think that shapes you in ways you don't
          notice until you're somewhere else — you learn early that nobody's
          going to go easy on you, that most people are more complicated than
          they look, and that the world right outside your window can be
          completely different from the one two towns over.
        </p>
        <p>
          i've watched enough to know we don't always live up to what we tell
          ourselves we are. not here, not anywhere. systems that forget the
          people inside them. conversations that turn into shouting matches
          before anyone actually listens.
        </p>

        <div class="about-callout">
          <span class="about-callout__bar" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <p class="about-callout__text">
            and i keep landing in the same place: the only thing that has ever
            actually fixed anything, in practice, is when someone decides to
            understand someone else first. not agree with them. not meet them
            halfway. just see them clearly, even when you disagree with
            everything they stand for. something shifts when you do that.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          i don't think unity means pretending things are fine. i think it means
          caring enough to show up when it's hard. empathy isn't softness — it
          takes more out of you than anger does, but it's the only thing i've
          ever seen actually move the needle.
        </p>
        <p>
          the world is messy and full of contradictions, and i still choose to
          believe people are worth it. not out of optimism. just — what's the
          alternative?
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 2: My Hobbies -->
    <section class="about-section" aria-label="My hobbies">
      <div class="about-section__header">
        <span class="about-section__icon" aria-hidden="true"><Compass /></span>
        <h2 class="about-section__title">my hobbies</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="about-divider" aria-hidden="true">
        <span class="about-divider__line"></span>
      </div>

      <div class="about-section__body">
        <p>
          urban exploration — urbex — is the one i have the hardest time
          explaining without it sounding like something it's not. some weekends
          i'll drive out to abandoned buildings, old factories, places that used
          to be something and got left behind. people hear that and think it's
          about danger, or trespassing, or getting a moody shot for instagram.
          it's none of those things.
        </p>

        <div class="about-callout">
          <span class="about-callout__bar" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <p class="about-callout__text">
            it's about standing in a room where hundreds of people used to work
            or live or learn, and now it's just peeling paint and silence.
            nothing is performing for you. it's just what's left when everything
            else moves on. there's an honesty in that i don't find many other
            places. it reminds me that nothing is permanent — and i mean that as
            a relief, not a tragedy.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          new jersey is actually a surprisingly good place for this. people
          forget how much industry this state used to hold. there's a lot of
          history quietly falling apart out there if you know where to look.
        </p>

        <p>
          aviation is the other one, and it's completely different in every way
          except that it also makes me feel like the world has edges. like
          things are containable. there's a moment right after takeoff where the
          wheels leave the ground, the noise changes, and everything below you
          gets small really fast. i've never found anything else that resets my
          brain quite like that.
        </p>

        <div class="about-inline-quote">
          <p>
            i can sit at a window seat and watch approach patterns for hours and
            not get bored. the way a plane turns final, lines up with a runway
            from miles away, and just commits — there's something incredibly
            deliberate about it. i find that calming in a way that's hard to
            articulate.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          and then there's the emergency services thing, which is harder to even
          call a hobby because it feels more like a permanent part of how my
          brain works. whenever i hear sirens, i stop. i notice. i'm already
          thinking about where they're headed, what happened, what's unfolding
          right now for whoever's in that situation. a structure fire? a medical
          call? someone just having the worst night of their life?
        </p>

        <div class="about-callout">
          <span class="about-callout__bar" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <p class="about-callout__text">
            there are people out there right now, at 3am, making split-second
            decisions that change someone's entire future, and most of the world
            is just asleep. i think about the weight of that a lot. the things
            that happen while nobody's watching.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          i also just like to go places. a road i haven't driven. a corner of a
          city i've never walked through. i'll get in the car with no real plan
          and see what's out there. growing up in jersey means you're an hour
          from almost everything — the city, the shore, the pine barrens, the
          mountains — so that habit got fed pretty well early on. i still can't
          shake it.
        </p>

        <p>
          and outside of all that: i love being around my friends. not doing
          anything in particular — just existing in the same space. driving
          around with the windows down. sitting in someone's kitchen at midnight
          talking about something that doesn't matter at all. the kind of time
          that never makes it into any story because nothing "happens" — but
          it's the stuff i'd actually miss most.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <footer class="page-footer">
      <BackRow href="/" label="back" />
    </footer>
  </article>
</Layout>
